14 WHEREAS, studies show a close relationship with an addicted person can become a source
15 of chaos, emotional upheaval, financial instability, and even violence, and children of parents
16 with a substance use disorder are at an increased risk of neglect or abuse, social isolation,
17 disrupted education, and developing a substance use disorder themselves; and
18 WHEREAS, employees who engage in heavy alcohol or illicit drug use are 33 percent less
19 productive than their coworkers, and addictions cost business owners over $750 billion each
20 year in lost revenue, profits, productivity, and healthcare costs; and
21 WHEREAS, statistics for Georgia show increasing numbers of drug overdose deaths, and
22 there is no significant difference between rates for drug overdose deaths in urban and rural
23 counties; and
24 WHEREAS, as a result of the addiction epidemic, every community in Georgia is
25 experiencing rising costs, academic challenges, threats to law enforcement officers and first
26 responders, impacts on marriages, and challenges for business owners and the workforce; and
27 WHEREAS, everyone deserves a chance at recovery from addiction including, but not
28 limited to, those in state, county, or city custody with the Department of Corrections or the
29 Department of Community Supervision, whether incarcerated, paroled, or on probation; and
30 WHEREAS, Georgia is a national leader in developing Certified Peer Specialists who are in
31 a position to provide returning citizens support during and upon completion of imprisonment
32 and on reentering the community; and
