33 WHEREAS, Georgia should promote programs and protocols for healthcare providers, law
34 enforcement and first responders, education leaders, faith leaders, business leaders, and local
35 governments to better address the addiction epidemic; and
36
37 WHEREAS, it would be beneficial for policymakers to study ways to embrace clinical and
38 peer led programs and protocols to enhance awareness of state Certified Peer Specialists to
39 serve those impacted by addiction through educational programs for healthcare providers,
40 law enforcement and first responders, education leaders, faith leaders, business leaders, and
41 local governments to better address the addiction epidemic to enhance collaboration and
42 integration.
43 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE:
44 (1) Creation of Senate study committee. There is created the Senate Study Committee
45 on Certified Peer Specialists, Addiction Recovery Programs, and Protocols.
46 (2) Members and officers. The committee shall be composed of six members of the
47 Senate to be appointed by the President of the Senate. The President shall designate a
48 member of the committee as chairperson of the committee.
49 (3) Powers and duties. The committee shall undertake a study of the conditions, needs,
50 issues, and problems mentioned above or related thereto and recommend any action or
51 legislation which the committee deems necessary or appropriate.
52 (4) Meetings. The chairperson shall call all meetings of the committee. The committee
53 may conduct such meetings at such places and at such times as it may deem necessary or
54 convenient to enable it to exercise fully and effectively its powers, perform its duties, and
55 accomplish the objectives and purposes of this resolution.
56 (5) Allowances and funding.
57 (A) The legislative members of the committee shall receive the allowances provided
58 for in Code Section 28-1-8 of the Official Code of Georgia Annotated.
